@{b}General notes and warnings@{ub}

It is suggested that you make a backup of (the unedited versions of) your
files before using the editor.
  If you want to save the changes you have made, you must do so explicitly
(eg. via the toolbar or menu). You are not warned about unsaved files
before the editor quits.
  It is not necessarily safe to set certain attributes to the maximum
allowed by the editor, as not every attribute has been exhaustively tested
for its allowable range. Also, the editor will allow you to set eg. your
current hit points to be higher than your maximum hit points, but doing
this is not recommended.
  Maximization buttons will not necessarily take every attribute to the
very highest value possible, to leave some headroom before attributes
overflow.
  Although the editor will let you load and save files with very long
filenames, the game(s) may have limitations on the maximum filename length
which might make it impossible to load such files into the game(s).
  Different game versions might use different file formats which may not
be compatible with the editor. Generally, where a WHDLoad slave is
available for a game, the editor is intended for use with that slave and
might not be intended for use with the floppy version. If the WHDLoad uses
Disk.1, Disk.2, etc. you may have to extract the relevant files from the
relevant disk image (generally the last (highest-numbered) disk of multi-
disk games is used for saved games).
  ADZs and ZIPped ADFs are not writable by WinUAE, so you should use (non-
write protected) ADFs instead of those.
  Files which you have previously hacked by hand might not be safe to load
into the game and/or editor.
  High score tables are generally automatically sorted for you before they
are saved.
  There are example vanilla saves for most games (all except Barbarian 2,
Beyond Dark Castle, Dragons of Flame, Garrison 1 & 2, Goal!, Grand Monster
Slam, Insanity Fight, Last Ninja Remix and Shadoworlds) provided in the
Examples/ directory, so that you can easily browse the capabilities of the
editor.
  While a subwindow is open, the main window cannot be used.
  Read the specific help node, if any, in this user manual, for your
particular game before doing any editing.
  The mouse wheel and/or cursor keys can generally be used to manipulate
listbrowsers and maps. You should ensure that no string or integer gadget
is activated (eg. by clicking in an empty part of the window), and
position the pointer over the gadget you want to manipulate. The numeric
keys can be used to manipulate maps.
  Extreme values might cause the game to have minor cosmetic (ie.
graphical) problems, such as misaligning of certain text (although this
should not cause any major problems). In other cases, the editor might be
somewhat more limiting of certain fields than is strictly possible.
  You should press ENTER or Tab after editing string or integer gadgets to
ensure everything is correctly updated.
  Cursor keys to scroll tables, etc. will not work while a string or
integer gadget has the keyboard input focus.
  Information shown by the editor may include "spoilers".
  Generally, only files pertaining to the Amiga versions of games are
supported. (The Dungeon Master and King's Quest et al. editors are an
exception to this.)
@endnode

@node Requ "System Requirements"

@{b}Hardware@{ub}         Required        about 16Mb free RAM
                 Recommended     1024*768 or higher Workbench
@{b}Firmware@{ub}         Required        Kickstart 3.1+
@{b}Software@{ub}         Required        AmigaOS 3.9 with Boing Bag 2 (at least)
                 Recommended     AmigaOS 3.2+
                                 OpenURL.library (if OS < 4.1.1)
                                 TCP/IP stack
                                 AmigaOS Enhancer Software Core (clock.gadget)
                                 AmigaOS 4.1FE (for OS4 version)

If your resolution is lower than 1024*768, you will probably need to run
the program on an autoscrolling screen. You cn use the @{"PUBSCREEN" link Usag} CLI
argument or WB tooltype to do this.

Generally, images are not loaded into memory until they are needed;
however, once loaded they are retained in memory until the program quits
(for speed, in case they are needed again).

clock.gadget and sketchboard.gadget are optional but recommended. If you
don't have sketchboard.gadget (part of OS3.2 and OS4), the graphics
editing subwindows will not be available.

If you have the Amiga Image Storage System (AISS) installed, you can
delete the images/aiss/ subdirectory.

The program will open its own screen if it needs to because your desktop
is not large enough.
  If you don't have quite enough RAM to run MCE, you can email us to ask
for a custom single-game build of MCE, which will have lower memory
requirements due to the omission of support for the other games. Although
these days just expanding your RAM is probably a better idea ;-)

For MorphOS users:

You need the appropriate ReAction classes installed. You can get these
classes from OS3.9 BB2 or (preferably) OS3.2.

For AmigaOS 4 users:

OS4.1FE is recommended so that you get BOOPSI menus (with imagery). The
BOOPSI menu subsystem assumes you have AISS installed (it is part of a
standard OS4.1FE install). The utility uses the MenuImageSize environment
variable when starting up to determine what size to make the menu imagery.
If this variable is is not present, the default is 16 pixels square. If
this variable is 0, menu imagery is not loaded nor shown.
@endnode

@node Usag "Usage"

@{b}CLI Arguments@{ub}

                                    @{b}MCE@{ub}

@{b}Format:    MCE@{ub} [[FUNCTION] <function>] [PUBSCREEN <pubscreen>]
           [SCREENWIDTH <width>] [SCREENHEIGHT <height>] [TEST]
           [FILE <file>]

@{b}Template:@{ub}  FUNCTION/N,PUBSCREEN/K,SCREENWIDTH/K/N,
           SCREENHEIGHT/K/N,TEST,FILE

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}   To edit game data files.

@{b}Specification:@{ub}

    function=<number>:
           the ordinal number of the function you wish to jump to.
           See @{"here" link Main} for the list of which numbers correspond
           to which games.

    pubscreen=<pubscreen>:
           the name of a public screen to open on (otherwise the default
           public screen is used). If this screen does not exist, MCE
           will create it as an autoscrolling screen with dimensions
           determined by the SCREENWIDTH and SCREENHEIGHT CLI arguments.

    screenwidth=<width>:
           minimum width to use when opening a new screen (defaults to
           1024).

    screenheight=<height>:
           minimum height to use when opening a new screen (defaults to
           768).

    test:
           this will cause the program to load the appropriate example
           file automatically. Eg. MCE 1 TEST will cause the program to
           start the Arazok's Tomb editor with its example file
           (PROGDIR:Examples/ArazoksTomb/ArazoksTomb.GAM) already loaded.

    file=<file>:
           a file to load for editing (requires use of the FUNCTION
           argument).

@{b}Workbench Tool Types@{ub}

FUNCTION=<function>
PUBSCREEN=<pubscreen>
SCREENWIDTH=<width>
SCREENHEIGHT=<height>
FILE=<file>

These are equivalent to the relevant CLI arguments.
@endnode

@node ArazoksTomb "Arazok's Tomb"

You *must* use the .GAM extension. Naming your saved game START.GAM is
probably unwise as it won't be listed by the game, and therefore you
won't be able to load it into the game.
  The .GAM file (eg. ArazoksTomb.GAM) is what is edited.
  The TOMBS file is used by the game to store the list of saved games.
If your saved game file is not listed in the TOMBS file, it will not be
shown by the game's "Project|Open..." file requester and thus you will not
be able to load it into the game.
  If the TOMBS file is present in the same directory as the .GAM file, it
will be updated automagically by the editor when saving.
  Saved games, and indeed most of the game's important files, are saved in
the misleadingly-named Empty/ directory of the game's disk.
@endnode

@node Psygnosis "Barbarian 2 (Psygnosis) & Obliterator"

@{b}Barbarian 2@{ub}

The WHDLoad slave (V2.0) of the game is assumed.
  Be cautious of adjusting the "Area" value. Some tested values within the
allowed range caused (harmless) graphics corruption.

Some in-game tips:
  To load a game, press "L" at the title screen (the one with the credits)
and then choose a slot number.
  To save a game, press "S" during play and then choose a slot number.

@{b}Obliterator@{ub}

The WHDLoad slave (V1.2) of the game is assumed.
  Note that only the FNIAA file is edited. The other ???AA files are
also part of the saved game and are required by the game, but they don't
contain anything relevant to MCE and should not be loaded into the editor.

Some in-game tips:
  To load a game, press Help, F1, Y, then any key.
  There are two ways to save a game:
  a) go to a shield regenerator (there are 4 of them in the game), click
     the "Enter" icon to walk into it, then press Y when asked about
     saving the game.
  b) collect a component (there are 5 of them in the game), then press Y
     when asked about saving the game.
@endnode

@node BardsTale "Bard's Tale 1-3 & Construction Set"

The program autodetects the type of file being opened. You can edit
character files (BT1 and BT2), roster files (a group of characters) (BT3
and BTCS), items files (BT1 and BT2), and saved games (BT3).
  For BT3 (at least), when playing the game, it is helpful to slow down
the CPU (eg. via WinUAE settings), to avoid excessive amounts of wandering
monster encounters.

Character/roster files:

The program allows considerable freedom to make alterations to the
characters; thus, discretion is advised. Don't forget to save your
character before quitting the program if you want to keep the changes
you have made.
  The checkboxes indicate whether the relevant item is "equipped" or not.
Next to each checkbox is an integer gadget which stores the quantity of
that item. 255 is a magic number meaning "unlimited". Clicking an item
slot will bring up a subwindow allowing you to change which item
is stored in that slot. If a particular item is not available in that
game, it will be shown in white.
  Values which can't be displayed by the game, eg. ST of 100 or more, are
shown in the game as asterisks (eg. "**"), "WOW", or similar. They still
work normally even if displayed in this manner.

Items files (BT1 and BT2 only):

The ITEMS file stores the list of what is sold by Garth's Equipment
Shoppe, the ledger of bank accounts (BT2 only) and the party's current
location (BT2 only), and some other unknown data (BT2 only).
  In the shoppe, 255 is a magic number meaning "unlimited".
  "Reset to defaults" will clear the ITEMS file to the factory default
state. For BT2, this includes setting the unknown area to the known
factory default values. This is the only situation in which MCE will
change the unknown area.

@{b}BT1@{ub}

The character (TPW.#?.C) or ITEMS file is what is edited.

@{b}BT2@{ub}

Images are used only for monsters/illusions.
Items can be carried by anyone.
The character (TPW.#?.C), ITEMS or game.save file is what is edited.

The current WHDLoad slave (V1.01) has some bugs that need these
once-only workarounds (assuming you are in the BardsTale2 directory):

    TYPE NIL: data/members/game.save ;(so you can save games)
    MAKEDIR data/membersbt           ;(so you can transfer BT1 characters)

Saved game files:

It is not currently possible to teleport from outside (wilderness/cities)
to a dungeon, or vice versa, nor to teleport from one dungeon to another
(nor from one level to another within the same dungeon). You can freely
change your outdoor location (including teleporting to/from any city or
the wilderness, and can change your dungeon location within the same
dungeon level.
  If you are in a dungeon, you can view and edit the dungeon name; this
only affects what is shown under the 3D view area in the game.

@{b}BT3@{ub}

Images are used for everyone.
Items can be carried only by players.
The THIEVES.INF or game.sav file is what is edited.
On the maps, blue squares/lines are special (eg. traps, teleports, items,
etc.). Not all special squares/lines are indicated. Up and down arrows
indicate stairs or an equivalent thereof. Grey squares are in darkness.
Hollow circles are boulders (which are passable on eg. the Amiga version
but impassable on eg. the Commodore 64 version). Your location and facing
direction is indicated by the white arrow. The coordinates used in the
editor are always stated as an offset east (E) and north (N) from the
bottom left corner of the map. In the game, they are often not stated in
this manner (instead being relative to eg. the entrance to the level).

@{b}BTCS@{ub}

Images are not used for anyone.
Items can be carried by anyone.
The ROSTER.CHR file is what is edited.
The sample scenario (Starlight Festival) is assumed, as far as items are
concerned.
@endnode

@node Bloodwych "Bloodwych & Extended Levels"

The "Extended Levels" are also known as "Data Disk 1".
  Low armour classes are better than high ones.
  The editor depends on the files being named correctly to determine which
game they belong to.
@endnode

@node BombJack "Bomb Jack 1"

This editor has been tested with V1.0 and V1.1 of the WHDLoad slave. It
will only handle uncompressed files; note that the "bj" and "platform.set"
files included with most distributions of V1.1 of the installed WHDLoad
slave are compressed. The ones provided in the Examples/BombJack1/
directory are uncompressed.
  "bj" is the main file that is edited (ie. the file you should specify
when loading or saving). However, "platform.set" is also loaded and thus
must also be present in its correct location.
  Levels 16-30 are always identical in all respects to levels 1-15
respectively (and thus are not separately editable).
  The right border of the playfield can have platforms over it; this is
not a bug in the editor.
  The darker red colour will colour-cycle in the game.
  The selected tile in the "Tiles" gadget will be outlined in black.
  The graphics used by the tiles can also be edited. This requires OS3.2+
or OS4 (for sketchboard.gadget), and exclusive access to 16 free pens. You
can either press the E key, click the "Edit Tile Graphics..." button, or
double-click a tile in the "Tiles" display.
  Editing of bombs is not currently supported.
@endnode

@node BuckRogers "Buck Rogers"

V1.2 of the WHDLoad slave is assumed.
  The WHO file is what is edited.
  Some skills require other skills as prerequisites. Medic skills are
exclusively for medics. Weapon specializations are only possible for
warriors. The editor does not really enforce these rules but the game
does.
  Note that your actual armour class in the game is modified by low or
high dexterity. The editor always assumes no dexterity modifier when
showing the armour class.
  The Mimic (INT) skill in the manual does not seem to be present in the
game.
@endnode

@node Epyx "California 1 & 2/Winter/World Games"

@{b}California Games 1@{ub}

For WHDLoad users: the MCP/menu.cmp file is what is edited. Note that
there is also a CALGAMES/menu.cmp file; this is @{i}not@{ui} what is edited!
  For floppy users: the MCP/menu.cmp file on disk 2 (the "Data Disk") is
what is edited. Note that there is also a CALGAMES/menu.cmp file on disk
1 (the "Program Disk"); this is @{i}not@{ui} what is edited!

@{b}California Games 2@{ub}

  The cgii file is what is edited.
  If you are using the WHDLoad version, you must delete the
CaliforniaGames2.highs file, if it exists, before editing.
  In the game, to see the high score table, move the bird to the car, then
press the fire button. If using the WHDLoad, you may also need to click
the left mouse button.
@endnode

@node CannonFodder "Cannon Fodder 1 & 2"

For Cannon Fodder 1, V2.0  or later of the WHDLoad slave is required.
  For Cannon Fodder 2, V1.12 or later of the WHDLoad slave is required.
  There doesn't seem to be any flag in the saved game file to indicate
whether it is for Cannon Fodder 1 or 2. You should set the "View/edit as"
gadget appropriately before or after loading the saved game.
  Kill counts can be up to 32767, but only the last 3 digits are shown by
the game.
  You can set the phase to anything you like, unlike in the game; ie. you
can begin part-way through a mission if you want.
  Setting the "Friendlies in reserve" gadget too high (in particular) can
cause the game to crash upon loading the saved game; therefore, you should
be @{i}very@{ui} careful when editing this.
  Having gaps in the middle of the heroes table or squad will probably
cause problems in-game.
  Filenames are supposed to be no more than 8 characters in length, and
composed of uppercase letters and/or numeric digits. Violating this rule
will cause the game's display of that filename to be corrupt, at least.
  Viewing and/or editing of graves is not currently supported.
  The number of men assigned to the squad for a particular phase seems to
be hard-coded by the game.
  Pressing the Help key during play will give 42 grenades and bazookas.
  There is a bug in the games: exceed 250 recruits and the recruitment
screen graphics will corrupt, causing a crash. If you play the game
untrained, there is no way you could reach this number anyway.
@endnode

@node ChambersOfShaolin "Chambers of Shaolin"

This editor is designed for the WHDLoad version (V1.2 was tested). The
floppy version seems to use a different format.
  There are many bugs in V1.0 and V1.1 of the WHDLoad slave; you should
use V1.2 (eg. pre-V1.2 slaves only support one character).
  However, pre-V1.2 rosters (16384 bytes) can still be loaded by
MCE; they are always saved in V1.2 format (16100 bytes).
  The "hidden" attributes are not displayed in-game. However, if these are
too low, some moves (eg. jump kick) may not be available. This applies at
least to the hidden #2-#4 values; the purpose of the hidden #1 value has
not been ascertained.
@endnode

@node ChampionsOfKrynn "Champions Of Krynn 1-3"

Note that characters are what is edited (not saved games).
  Champions of Krynn 2 is aka Death Knights of Krynn.
  Champions of Krynn 3 is aka the Dark Queen of Krynn.
  For Dark Queen of Krynn, editing of spells is not currently supported
(your existing spell list will be preserved, but not shown).
  Note that the game/hint/DQK_HexCodes.lha document on Aminet is
incorrect in some particulars and thus should not be relied upon.
@endnode

@node CitadelOfVras "Citadel of Vras"

The game detects attempts to alter certain fields and will quit in such
situations. Therefore those fields are read-only in the editor, for now at
least. You can freely teleport around, change your inventory, etc. Eg. you
can give yourself expensive items and then teleport to the shop
(coordinates X6,Y3,L1) to sell them.

In the map, special squares are shown in blue. The "Contents" gadget tells
more information about them. Walls are shown in black. Normal doors are
shown in green. Barriers between one square and the next (eg. walls of
fire, gaping holes, speaking doors) are shown in red. Your location and
facing direction is indicated by the white arrow.

The 'E,N' coordinate system is used in-game (eg. for the Location
power). The 'X,Y' coordinate system is used in MCE (eg. for ladder
destinations).

There is a HD-installed version of this game at
http://amigan.1emu.net/aw/ .

Notes for playing the game: You must press the spacebar at the title
screen. When asked for text (eg. when naming a newly created character),
you must click in the string gadget before typing. The game will not
allow you to adventure until you have five characters in the party.
@endnode

@node Scrabble "Computer Scrabble Deluxe"

This game has several names, eg. "Computer Scrabble" (USA), "Computer
Scrabble Deluxe" (Europe). They are all basically the same and can all be
edited.
  The colours used by the editor match those used by the game. They are:

    Dark  green : empty ordinary square
    Light red   : empty double letter score
    Dark  blue  : empty triple letter score
    Light red   : empty double word score
    Dark  red   : empty triple word score
    Light yellow: square with a tile on it
                  Black text on light yellow are normal letters.
                  Blue  text on light yellow are wildcard (blank) letters.

In the "Pile" and "Rack" groups, the wildcard (blank) tiles are
represented by spaces.
  Unfortunately the game gets the square types for the board from an
internal table and thus ignores the square types that are stored in the
saved game file. Therefore, it isn't possible to change the number and
arrangement of bonus squares (triple word scores, etc.).
@endnode

@node ConflictEurope "Conflict Europe"

Amsterdam does not exist in the game (nor editor), even though the Dutch
army does exist. And likewise for Rome (which would be offscreen anyway).
  In the fifth scenario ("What If?"), Poland and Romania are neutral. The
game shows their armies as yellow but their cities as red in this
situation. The editor follows the same convention.
  Note that the game only allows loading and saving during the movement
phase (ie. not during the assault nor rebuild phases). Also note that each
turn is 2 days long, ie. even-numbered days are not used by the game (nor
the editor).
@endnode

@node DarkCastle "Dark Castle & Beyond Dark Castle"

