@node FaeryTaleAdventure "Faery Tale Adventure"

The outdoor map is shown at a 1:64 ratio (ie. 1 pixel on the editor map is
64 units as shown by the X and Y gadgets). Some edges of the outdoor map
(containing empty sea) are not shown. The indoor map is shown at a 1:32
ratio.
  The cursor (arrow) keys can be used to alter your location on the map,
with these qualifier keys:

    Ctrl   - move to edge
    Alt    - move by 10 editor pixels (320 or 640 units)
    (none) - move by  1 editor pixel  ( 32 or  64 units)
    Shift  - move by                            1 unit

Turning on the trainer allows these cheats during the game:

    ARROW KEYS____Move very fast over any terrain.
    'B'__________________________Summon gold swan.
    'R'___________________________Rescue princess.
    '='_______________________Display coordinates.
    'F9'________________Increase time by one hour.
    'F10'_________________Location in coordinates.

There are two ways to access the hint oracle:
  1. You can hover over a gadget to show the hint as a tooltip; or
  2. You can click on an image to show the hint in a requester. (The
pointer will change from yellow to red while hovering over the image if it
has a hint available.)
@endnode

@node SilentSoftware "Firepower & Turbo"

The graphics used by the tiles can also be edited. This requires OS3.2+
or OS4 (for sketchboard.gadget), and exclusive access to 32 free pens. You
can either press the E key, click the "Edit Tile Graphics..." button, or
double-click a tile in the "Tiles" display.

@{b}Firepower@{ub}

"T1", "T2", etc. (in the MapP1, MapP2 or MapP3 directory) is the main file
that is edited (ie. the file you should specify when loading or saving).
However, "tiles" (in the gr/ directory) is also loaded and thus must also
be present in its correct location.
  The selected tile in the "Tiles" gadget will be outlined. The outline
colours have these meanings:

    Black: ordinary tile.
    Red:   this tile cannot be placed on the map.
    Brown: brown version of this tile will be placed.
    Green: green version of this tile will be placed.

You can toggle between placing brown or green tiles by using the "Colour"
gadget.
  When editing graphics, the brown version of the tile is assumed. In the
game (and on the editor map), colours 28..31 will be replaced with colours
20..23 respectively when drawing the green version of the tile.
  For a 1-player game, the game randomly chooses one of the five maps
"T1".."T5" in the MapP1 directory. Maps for the 1-player game should have
zero green garages and zero brown flag buildings.
  For a local 2-player game, the game randomly chooses one of the five
maps "T1".."T5" in the MapP2 directory.
  For a modem 2-player game, the game uses the "T1" map in the MapP3
directory.
  Maps for the 2-player games should have (only) one green garage and
at least one brown flag building. The included example map is a 2-player
map.
  You can also load half maps, eg. as supported by the FME (Firepower Map
Editor) utility.

@{b}Turbo@{ub}

"T1", "T2" or "T3" (in the maps/ directory) is the main file that is
edited (ie. the file you should specify when loading or saving). However,
"tiles" (in the gr/ directory) is also loaded and thus must also be
present in its correct location.
  "T3" is is the bottommost (ie. first) level.
  The first nine tiles are always monochrome.
  The tenth tile (the entirely blank one) cannot be edited.
  The remaining tiles can be edited in 32 colours.
  The selected tile in the "Tiles" gadget will be outlined. The outline
colours have these meanings:

    Black: ordinary tile.
    Red:   graphics of this tile cannot be edited.
@endnode

@node Garrison "Garrison 1 & 2"

This editor is intended for the WHDLoad version of the games (V1.1 of the
slave was tested). Disk.2 (the scenario disk) is what is edited.
  Now you too can make 128 new levels and sell them for £24.95 :-/

There are some minor graphical differences between the game and the
editor:

  a) floor designs used in the editor do not necessarily match those
     used by the relevant game for a particular level;
  b) tile $20 has different imagery in the game depending on the level.
     In the editor, these are always shown with the same imagery
     regardless of the level;
  c) some tiles are drawn differently by the game depending on what tiles
     they are adjacent to; and
  d) the start position is shown in purple by the editor as a courtesy,
     whereas these are invisible in the game.
@endnode

@node Goal "Goal!"

Disk.3 (the custom roster disk) is what is edited.
  As that disk is not a normal AmigaDOS format, the 40 "files" on that
disk are only accessible through the editor and game. The entire disk is
always loaded or saved when the editor's Open and Save commands are used.
