@node Rogue "HackLite/Larn/Moria/Rogue"

You can edit saved games or hall of fame (high score table) files. MCE
will detect the file type and configure itself accordingly.

@{b}HackLite@{ub}

HackLite ][ (V2.8.1 from Home Brew Software in 1993 was tested)
(eg. from http://aminet.net/game/role/HackLite2_1.lha).
  Note that HackLite (at least) deletes your saved game after loading it.
Also, HackLite has a bug whereby the game may refuse to save to a volume
such as a large hard disk, thinking it is full. A workaround is to save to
a smaller device instead, such as RAM: or a floppy disk.
  Moving yourself on the map will cause a "ghost" image of yourself to
remain in your old position (until you walk over it in the game). This is
harmless.

@{b}Larn@{ub}

This is for Caverns of Larn 12.0B (eg. from Fish Disk #63).
  Note that Larn deletes your saved game after loading it.
  Also, your Larn: assign must be set correctly or the game will crash as
soon as you enter the dungeon. The game also seems to crash if you die in
the volcano, at least on our system.
  The "Reveal All" button will cause all squares of all levels to be
marked as explored, so that the game will show you the entire level. It
does not have any effect on the editor (because the editor will always
show the entire level regardless of whether it has been revealed or not).
Additionally, it will change invisible (ie. untriggered) traps to their
visible (triggered) equivalents. Note that the "Maximize Character"
function performs a "Reveal All" for you as part of its functionality.
  Untriggered traps, which are invisible in the game, are shown in the
editor as hollow white boxes. Monsters are not shown in the editor.
  There are separate high score tables for winners and losers (though both
stored in the same file). Entries #1..#10 of the high score table are the
winners table, and entries #11..#20 are the losers table.
  Launching the game with the -s CLI argument (ie. "Larn -s") will show
the high score tables.
  Volcanco levels are designated "V1".."V3" by the game; the high score
editor designates these as "11".."13" (the saved game editor designates
them variously according to what dungeon levels have been visited).

@{b}Moria@{ub}

UMoria V5.5.0 from Henrik Harmsen in 1992 (eg. from
http://aminet.net/game/role/Moria_gfx_1.2.lha) is intended. You can get
the source code for the UNIX version of it from
http://beej.us/moria/files/source/um5.5.tar.Z .
  The game uses an "exceptional strength" system similar to Advanced
Dungeons & Dragons. Attribute values (eg. strength) of 19 or more in the
editor correspond to 18/01 and higher. Eg. 255 in the editor means 18/237
in the game.
  Not everything is shown on the map. Also, the same imagery is used
for eg. shops, whereas the game has different imagery for each.
  The way the game is designed is that only the map of the current level
is actually stored in the saved game file.
  The game keeps a lock on the high scores file while it is running;
therefore quit the game before saving the high scores table.
  Moving yourself on the map will cause a "ghost" image of yourself to
remain in your old position (until you walk over it in the game). This is
harmless.

@{b}Rogue@{ub}

This is intended for the Epyx version. (*Not*, for example,
http://aminet.net/game/role/Rogue11.lha). V1.48 from Epyx in 1986 was
tested. The version number is shown by pressing the 'V' key during play.
  denis2342's V1.48.1 edition from 2023
(https://forum.amiga.org/index.php?topic=75893.0) is supported for saved
games, but not for high score tables.
@endnode

@node HeroesOfTheLance "Heroes of the Lance & Dragons of Flame"

