@node KingsQuest "King's Quest 1-3 & Space Quest 1"

Items cannot be moved to different rooms due to the way the game's logic
works (ie. there is no logic in the game to handle items being in the
wrong room).
  Getting items via the editor might not work completely for some items,
as the game uses various variables to keep track of inventory contents and
status, differing on a per-item basis. The most reliable method is to
teleport yourself to the item and then pick it up in-game.
  Lower speed values are faster. You can use the editor set the speed to
other values than just those the game has keywords for:
  Speed 0 (unlimited) is called "fast" or "fastest" depending on the
game version.
  Speed 1 is not available in-game or is called "fast" depending on the
game version.
  Speed 2 is always called "normal".
  Speed 3 is not available in-game. It could be considered "slowish" as it
is intermediate in speed between normal and slow.
  Speed 4 is always called "slow".
  During the games, you can view the game and AGI version numbers, and
enter the trainer ("debug mode"), by pressing Alt-D for most games, or by
typing RATS ASS for KQ3 for MS-DOS. In this mode (which lasts until you
enter a new room), you can use these commands:

    TP                Teleport to the appropriate room.
    POS               Set ego's X and Y positions.
    GET OBJECT        Put the appropriate object by ID into the player's
                      inventory.
    OBJECT|SP         Give status on the appropriate object.
    SET VAR           Set a chosen variable (0..255) to a given value
                      (0..255).
    SHOW VAR          Display the value (0..255) of a variable (0..255).
    SET FLAG          Set the appropriate flag (0..255).
    RESET FLAG        Reset (clears) the appropriate flag (0..255).
    SHOW FLAG         Display info on a flag (can be either set or not
                      set).

and these keys:

    F6                Display priority layers for the current room. 
    F10               Display info on memory use.

For King's Quest 3, these additional commands are available:

    ENCHANTER STATUS  Gives a detailed status of Manannan, where he is,
                      when he'll return, etc.
 or WIZARD STATUS
    DO CHORE          Sets task as done.
    SLEEP ENCHANTER
 or SLEEP WIZARD      Puts Manannan to sleep for twenty hours.
    BYE BYE ENCHANTER
 or BYE BYE WIZARD    Kills Manannan (this doesn't work properly though).
    PUT UP SPELL      Gives all inventory items.
    PUT UP MOUNTAIN   Changes game state to arrival at the kingdom of
                      Daventry.
    PUT UP BOAT       Changes game state to the beginning of the sailing
                      trip.

These versions were used for testing:

    KQ1 for Amiga     Game 1.0U, AGI interpreter 2.082, WHDLoad slave 2.0
    KQ1 for MS-DOS    Game 2.0F, AGI interpreter 2.917
    KQ2 for Amiga     Game 2.0J, AGI interpreter 2.316, WHDLoad slave 2.0
    KQ2 for MS-DOS    Game 2.1 , AGI interpreter 2.411
    KQ3 for Amiga     Game 1.01, AGI interpreter 2.090, WHDLoad slave 1.1
    KQ3 for MS-DOS    Game 2.14, AGI interpreter 2.936
    SQ1 for Amiga     Game 1.2 , AGI interpreter 2.082, WHDLoad slave 1.3A
    SQ1 for MS-DOS    Game 2.2 , AGI interpreter 2.917

Other versions and platforms may work but have not been tested; please
advise us of any issues encountered.

@{b}King's Quest 1@{ub}

Only the AGI version is supported, not the later "enhanced" SCI version.
  For MS-DOS files, teleporting will not be effective immediately; when
you reload the game and walk to another room, the new room will be next to
the specified room, in the appropriate direction. In other words, after
reloading, you should walk out of the room, turn around and walk back in,
and you will be in your desired room.
  For Amiga files, teleporting yourself via the editor around can cause
remnant animations from the previous screen to occur, eg. castle flags
waving. This does not appear to cause any harm and everything should be
back to normal once you walk or swim to another screen.
  Some items (rope, necklace, locket, glass shoes) do not appear to have
been fully implemented in the game, although they can be added (via the
editor) to your inventory. For MS-DOS files, they are not even partially
implemented.
  To see the ending, load the vanilla example, click "Maximize Game",
and set your location to the throne room.

@{b}King's Quest 2@{ub}

For MS-DOS files, teleporting will not be effective immediately; when
you reload the game and walk to another room, the new room will be next to
the specified room, in the appropriate direction. In other words, after
reloading, you should walk out of the room, turn around and walk back in,
and you will be in your desired room.
  For Amiga files, teleporting yourself via the editor around can cause
remnant animations from the previous screen to occur. This does not appear
to cause any harm and everything should be back to normal once you walk or
swim to another screen.
  To see the ending, load the vanilla example, click "Maximize Game",
and set your location to Valanice. Then, in the game, just type HOME.

@{b}King's Quest 3@{ub}

Items marked with '*' are forbidden by the wizard Manannan.
  To see the ending, load the vanilla example, click "Maximize Game",
and set your location to the hall of the castle. Then, in the game, just
walk left. You should not actually set your location to the throne room
(or any other room that will immediately play music) as this will cause an
error upong reloading into the game.

@{b}Space Quest 1@{ub}

Teleporting will not be effective immediately; when you reload the game
and walk to another room, the new room will be next to the specified room,
in the appropriate direction. In other words, after reloading, you should
walk out of the room, turn around and walk back in, and you will be in
your desired room.
  The logic that the game uses to determine whether you can exit from the
four sides of the screen is based on the new room, not the old room, even
though you are, at first, in the old room. Eg. teleporting to the victory
screen will not work because the Victory screen has no exits, and
therefore you will be unable to leave your old room.
  You can change your uniform in the editor, but note that this will not
change the in-game imagery for your character. If you have changed your
uniform using the editor, you should not eg. fire your gun ("pulse ray")
in the game (you will not need to anyway, if you are wearing the "Sarien
uniform w/ helmet") as the view expected by the game is not loaded.
  Note that there are two inventory slots for survival kits; this is not a
bug in the editor.
  To see the ending, load the vanilla example, click "Maximize Game",
and set your location to Deltaur #53. Then, in the game, walk right.
When you reach the next room, walk into the right elevator. Now walk to
the shuttle. When you reach it, type ENTER SHIP and then PUSH BUTTON.
@endnode

