introductory sequence is occurring).
  Turning off JIT or setting the CPU emulation speed to "Approximate A500/
A1200 or cycle-exact" in the WinUAE settings will improve compatibility
(at least for V1.2 of the WHDLoad slave).

Coordinates in the game are shown as AA-CC. Ie. only the coarse
coordinates are shown. (Red coordinates in the game represent negative
numbers (eg. red 12 means -12), black coordinates represent positive
numbers. ** in the game represents a coordinate of -100 or less (red)
or +100 or more (black).) Editing of coordinates in the third dimension
(ie. altitude) is not currently supported. Indoors (ie. underground)
location editing has not been tested.
  In the editor, they are shown as AAA.BBBBB-CCC.DDDDD, where B and D are
the fine coordinates (0..65535).
  The black dot indicates your location. White dots indicate the locations
of items and props.
  You can scroll the list of items/props with the cursor keys, or via
mouse, either by using the scrollbar or by holding down the left mouse
button and moving beyond the borders of the "Locations" group.
  Although there are 11 slots, normally the game will only let you use 10
of them. Eg. if you have 11 items, you must drop (with the cursor down
key) 2 in the game before you can pick up another (with the cursor up
key). The item stack is a FIFO (first-in, first-out) stack. It might be
necessary to drop and re-get items before you can use them.
  In the "Locations" group, you can select a button and then click on
the map to move things. But older versions of layout.gadget have a bug
whereby your first click is ignored. This has been fixed for OS3.2.2.
